00:29:35,283 --> 00:29:36,723
It's comfy in here.

506
00:29:36,723 --> 00:29:38,323
I mean, the seat's pretty good,

507
00:29:38,323 --> 00:29:41,083
everything's covered in
expensive materials,

508
00:29:41,083 --> 00:29:43,883
I can see out of the thing
perfectly well.

509
00:29:43,883 --> 00:29:46,683
I mean, I wouldn't call it a
luxury motorcar,

510
00:29:46,683 --> 00:29:49,683
but it's beautifully built.

511
00:29:49,683 --> 00:29:52,083
And it's practical-ish.

512
00:29:52,083 --> 00:29:56,323
I mean, it's fitted with the largest
battery of any electric vehicle,

513
00:29:56,323 --> 00:30:00,003
so it'll do 300 miles on a
single charge.

514
00:30:00,003 --> 00:30:03,603
As products from companies
you've never heard of go,

515
00:30:03,603 --> 00:30:06,683
it's all very convincing.

516
00:30:06,683 --> 00:30:09,883
How much they want you to pay
for it, on the other hand,

517
00:30:09,883 --> 00:30:13,443
might take a little more convincing.

518
00:30:13,443 --> 00:30:16,163
Because this upstart costs -

519
00:30:16,163 --> 00:30:17,323
wait for it -

520
00:30:17,323 --> 00:30:19,803
£2 million.

521
00:30:19,803 --> 00:30:21,563
Now, that's not Ferrari money,

522
00:30:21,563 --> 00:30:23,643
that's not even Lamborghini money,

523
00:30:23,643 --> 00:30:25,403
that's Bugatti money.

524
00:30:25,403 --> 00:30:27,403
It's private jet money.

525
00:30:27,403 --> 00:30:29,723
That's... That's punchy.

526
00:30:32,763 --> 00:30:36,323
Luckily, the Nevera does
have a little trick up its sleeve

527
00:30:36,323 --> 00:30:41,283
that might go some way to justifying
its enormous price tag.

528
00:30:41,283 --> 00:30:47,243
A little trick that requires
a rather long runway to demonstrate.

529
00:30:47,243 --> 00:30:49,883
Now, I probably should have
mentioned this earlier,

530
00:30:49,883 --> 00:30:54,443
but even by conventional supercar
standards, the Nevera is...

531
00:30:54,443 --> 00:30:56,443
It's quite powerful.

532
00:30:56,443 --> 00:30:59,523
You see, it's got one electric motor
for each wheel,

533
00:30:59,523 --> 00:31:04,443
combined power output just under
2,000 horsepower.

534
00:31:05,523 --> 00:31:07,803
That is a lot.

535
00:31:09,363 --> 00:31:11,483
So, what does it feel like?

536
00:31:25,483 --> 00:31:26,803
Oh, my Lord.

537
00:31:29,083 --> 00:31:30,603
That's 100.

538
00:31:31,843 --> 00:31:33,403
130.

539
00:31:33,403 --> 00:31:35,363
150.

540
00:31:35,363 --> 00:31:37,203
170.

541
00:31:37,203 --> 00:31:38,403
This is ridiculous.

542
00:31:38,403 --> 00:31:39,723
190.

543
00:31:39,723 --> 00:31:42,363
That's 200. She's still pulling.

544
00:31:42,363 --> 00:31:44,963
That's 211, 212.

545
00:31:47,203 --> 00:31:51,963
Right, that is absolutely
mind scramblingly fast.

546
00:31:55,403 --> 00:31:57,283
Good Lord!

547
00:31:57,283 --> 00:32:01,083
That's not driving, that's an
out-of-body experience.

548
00:32:01,083 --> 00:32:07,283
In fact, the Nevera accelerates
to 60mph in under 2 seconds.

549
00:32:07,283 --> 00:32:11,203
And whereas electric cars up to
now have always run out of puff

550
00:32:11,203 --> 00:32:13,883
the further north of 100 they go,

551
00:32:13,883 --> 00:32:19,083
this car is limited to 219.

552
00:32:19,083 --> 00:32:21,403
Now, what we need here is a bit
of context.

553
00:32:21,403 --> 00:32:26,043
To my left, we have a
Lamborghini Aventador SVJ.

554
00:32:26,043 --> 00:32:27,963
ENGINE REVS

555
00:32:27,963 --> 00:32:29,443
By any standards,

556
00:32:29,443 --> 00:32:31,083
a very, very fast car.

557
00:32:34,443 --> 00:32:35,963
Watch what happens now.

558
00:32:35,963 --> 00:32:38,083
LAMBORGHINI ENGINE REVS

559
00:32:39,523 --> 00:32:42,763
Three, two, one, go!

560
00:32:42,763 --> 00:32:44,043
Bye-bye.

561
00:32:46,283 --> 00:32:47,843
Just disappearing.

562
00:32:49,363 --> 00:32:51,323
I can't begin to describe...

563
00:32:51,323 --> 00:32:53,643
He's not even there, he's gone.

564
00:32:56,563 --> 00:32:59,083
I can barely see him in my mirror.

565
00:33:02,763 --> 00:33:04,083
Over the line.

566
00:33:07,763 --> 00:33:10,523
That spec in the mirror
that I can hardly see

567
00:33:10,523 --> 00:33:13,483
is one of the fastest
Lamborghinis ever made.

568
00:33:17,283 --> 00:33:19,843
It's not... It's not a beating,
it's a mauling.

569
00:33:22,843 --> 00:33:25,643
Tell you what, the old guard better
get ready for it,

570
00:33:25,643 --> 00:33:28,683
cos this is... This is all new
for me.

571
00:33:28,683 --> 00:33:30,643
It's all new for everyone.

572
00:33:31,923 --> 00:33:34,603
The remarkable thing about
the Nevera

573
00:33:34,603 --> 00:33:38,763
isn't that it's the fastest
accelerating road car ever built,

574
00:33:38,763 --> 00:33:43,003
it's the sheer scale of the leap
in performances made.

575
00:33:45,603 --> 00:33:47,003
Round two.

576
00:33:47,003 --> 00:33:49,643
Let's give the Aventador
a better chance this time.

577
00:33:49,643 --> 00:33:52,163
It's 300 metres up the runway

578
00:33:52,163 --> 00:33:55,243
and we're going to run
over a standing mile.

579
00:33:56,403 --> 00:33:57,443
Watch this.

580
00:33:59,163 --> 00:34:01,003
ENGINE REVS

581
00:34:06,763 --> 00:34:10,323
Three, two, one, go!

582
00:34:10,323 --> 00:34:11,723
Here we go.

583
00:34:11,723 --> 00:34:13,123
It can't do it, can it?

584
00:34:13,123 --> 00:34:16,043
How can it possibly catch
that Lamborghini?

585
00:34:18,963 --> 00:34:20,163
We're catching it.

586
00:34:21,843 --> 00:34:23,643
We're catching it.

587
00:34:23,643 --> 00:34:25,883
I can't believe this.

588
00:34:25,883 --> 00:34:28,043
It's absolutely absurd.

589
00:34:30,043 --> 00:34:31,283
Oh, my Lord.

590
00:34:31,283 --> 00:34:33,363
HE LAUGHS

591
00:34:33,363 --> 00:34:35,483
That's outrageous!

592
00:34:35,483 --> 00:34:38,843
I'm doing 218, 219mph.

593
00:34:42,083 --> 00:34:43,523
Wow!

594
00:34:45,003 --> 00:34:47,723
And it doesn't stop there.

595
00:34:47,723 --> 00:34:51,603
In case all that straight
line fun wears off,

596
00:34:51,603 --> 00:34:55,483
Rimac says they've been to town
on the handling, too.

597
00:34:55,483 --> 00:34:58,563
Each wheel's motor is
independently controlled,

598
00:34:58,563 --> 00:35:02,003
so the way the Nevera drives
can be transformed

599
00:35:02,003 --> 00:35:03,723
at the flick of a switch.

600
00:35:04,803 --> 00:35:06,523
A switch that includes...

601
00:35:08,083 --> 00:35:09,243
..drift mode.

602
00:35:12,403 --> 00:35:14,883
TYRES SCREECH

603
00:35:16,043 --> 00:35:17,523
Dear me!

604
00:35:17,523 --> 00:35:21,123
Mate! This is a drift beast
like I've never been in before.

605
00:35:28,403 --> 00:35:31,123
TYRES SCREECH

606
00:35:38,123 --> 00:35:39,683
It's so easy.

607
00:35:39,683 --> 00:35:41,963
It's just wind the lock on,

608
00:35:41,963 --> 00:35:43,243
bit of throttle.

609
00:35:46,563 --> 00:35:47,803
Whoa-ho-ho!

610
00:35:47,803 --> 00:35:49,363
Oh, they're clever.

611
00:35:49,363 --> 00:35:51,163
They're clever. And it's fun.

612
00:35:51,163 --> 00:35:52,883
It's fun and it's silly.

613
00:36:00,043 --> 00:36:01,923
This car slides.

614
00:36:01,923 --> 00:36:04,523
It feels fantastic
when it's moving around.

615
00:36:04,523 --> 00:36:06,043
I know it doesn't have the noise,

616
00:36:06,043 --> 00:36:09,723
but when you've got
this performance,

617
00:36:09,723 --> 00:36:11,523
I'm starting to wonder if you care.

618
00:36:13,723 --> 00:36:18,763
Of course, we have seen this sort
of digital drifting before.

619
00:36:18,763 --> 00:36:22,803
In recent years, it's become pretty
much the standard party mode

620
00:36:22,803 --> 00:36:25,763
for performance cars
all over the market.

621
00:36:27,763 --> 00:36:29,883
But this being Rimac,

622
00:36:29,883 --> 00:36:33,323
in the Nevera there's also an
afterparty.

623
00:36:34,523 --> 00:36:36,323
Four-wheel drive,

624
00:36:36,323 --> 00:36:38,603
no traction control,

625
00:36:38,603 --> 00:36:40,763
all wheels spinning.

626
00:36:40,763 --> 00:36:41,923
Here we go.

627
00:36:43,883 --> 00:36:45,963
TYRES SCREECH

628
00:36:48,883 --> 00:36:50,123
Good God.

629
00:37:01,323 --> 00:37:03,483
What is going on in this car?

630
00:37:04,723 --> 00:37:07,163
We just did a tyre in one skid.

631
00:37:08,283 --> 00:37:10,043
That's just ridiculous.

632
00:37:10,043 --> 00:37:14,603
Mr Rimac, you are my kind
of lunatic.

633
00:37:14,603 --> 00:37:16,203
Yes, you are!

634
00:37:21,043 --> 00:37:23,123
I don't quite know what to say
about that.

635
00:37:28,723 --> 00:37:29,803
Wow.

636
00:37:33,963 --> 00:37:36,443
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

637
00:37:42,043 --> 00:37:44,083
Mind blown.

638
00:37:44,083 --> 00:37:47,083
Mind blown.  That is
absolutely bonkers.

639
00:37:47,083 --> 00:37:49,403
It went past that Lambo
like it was standing still.

640
00:37:49,403 --> 00:37:52,723
It's extraordinary. It's not like
anything I've ever driven before.

641
00:37:52,723 --> 00:37:54,163
It's that fast.

642
00:37:54,163 --> 00:37:56,923
The day after I drove it,
I actually felt a bit queasy.

643
00:37:56,923 --> 00:37:59,243
I don't know whether that's the high
voltage cables

644
00:37:59,243 --> 00:38:01,083
or whether my kidneys are bruised.

645
00:38:01,083 --> 00:38:05,443
I mean, it's crazy.  So you're saying
your innards have been Rimac'd?

646
00:38:05,443 --> 00:38:08,003
Not a nice sounding phrase,
but that's correct.

647
00:38:08,003 --> 00:38:09,283
THEY LAUGH

648
00:38:09,283 --> 00:38:11,683
And these lads are now in
charge of Bugatti?

649
00:38:11,683 --> 00:38:13,363
Yeah, they are. It's very businessy.

650
00:38:13,363 --> 00:38:16,363
They were bought by Porsche, who've
now put them in charge of Bugatti.

651
00:38:16,363 --> 00:38:18,883
I mean, the whole world's been
changed upside down

652
00:38:18,883 --> 00:38:19,963
in a matter of years.

653
00:38:19,963 --> 00:38:21,883
So is that it, electric's won?

654
00:38:21,883 --> 00:38:24,443
Should all petrol supercars
just give up now?

655
00:38:24,443 --> 00:38:25,603
It's not as simple as that.

656
00:38:25,603 --> 00:38:27,843
They need to give up on
the acceleration and speed race

657
00:38:27,843 --> 00:38:30,283
because these things are so fast,
there's no catching up.

658
00:38:30,283 --> 00:38:32,203
Petrol needs to trade
on emotion now.

659
00:38:32,203 --> 00:38:34,443
Gear changes, sound, go lightweight,

660
00:38:34,443 --> 00:38:37,603
but don't try and out-accelerate
this monster cos you will lose.

661
00:38:37,603 --> 00:38:39,123
Well, with that in mind,

662
00:38:39,123 --> 00:38:41,563
when are we going to get
it on the track?

663
00:38:41,563 --> 00:38:44,403
Slight problem. It's so fast,
we've got to update the software

664
00:38:44,403 --> 00:38:46,723
on The Stig because he can't deal
with it just yet,

665
00:38:46,723 --> 00:38:48,563
but hopefully next year.

666
00:38:48,563 --> 00:38:50,563
OK, watch this space.

667
00:38:50,563 --> 00:38:52,963
But now it's time to get back
to Thailand,

668
00:38:52,963 --> 00:38:57,923
where Fred was properly in a bad
way - coughing, shivering, the lot.

669
00:38:57,923 --> 00:39:00,963
So Chris and I did what any true
mates would do.

670
00:39:00,963 --> 00:39:03,723
Left him to it
and enjoyed the rest of our trip!

671
00:39:03,723 --> 00:39:05,163
CROWD CHEERS

672
00:39:05,163 --> 00:39:06,603
LAUGHING

673
00:39:11,203 --> 00:39:13,763
With Flintoff left behind
in Bangkok,

674
00:39:13,763 --> 00:39:17,003
me and Harris had pointed
our pick-ups north.

675
00:39:22,563 --> 00:39:26,243
Our mission now was to haul a
much-needed cargo

676
00:39:26,243 --> 00:39:30,563
to a remote hill village
near the border with Laos.

677
00:39:30,563 --> 00:39:34,283
Nice to have been given
something useful to do.

678
00:39:34,283 --> 00:39:38,923
Plus, hauling for free meant
we'd had to start doing things

679
00:39:38,923 --> 00:39:40,443
the local way.

680
00:39:51,683 --> 00:39:54,803
I've got to be honest, I'm happy
with the extra weight in the back.

681
00:39:54,803 --> 00:39:57,483
It just gives the car a bit
more stability.

682
00:39:57,483 --> 00:40:01,083
And whereas when we first saw
something overloaded coming past us,

683
00:40:01,083 --> 00:40:03,603
we sort of whooped with joy,
they're probably going,

684
00:40:03,603 --> 00:40:05,603
"Amateur. We could get another
bale on that."

685
00:40:05,603 --> 00:40:09,963
I know, it's bonkers, isn't it?

686
00:40:09,963 --> 00:40:16,083
It was bonkers, particularly
given two important points.

687
00:40:17,403 --> 00:40:19,883
I've got one thing on my mind,
though, Pad -

688
00:40:19,883 --> 00:40:25,323
I've never seen so much fresh grass,
so why are we carrying grass?

689
00:40:26,283 --> 00:40:28,403
I've seen quite a few cows
knocking about,

690
00:40:28,403 --> 00:40:30,723
maybe we're taking them
a bit to feed.

691
00:40:30,723 --> 00:40:33,683
Do cows eat hay or is that horses?

692
00:40:35,923 --> 00:40:37,643
They do eat hay, yes.

693
00:40:39,523 --> 00:40:43,003
I reckon we're going feeding
a load of cows.

694
00:40:43,003 --> 00:40:47,443
Whatever the bales
were actually for, though,

695
00:40:47,443 --> 00:40:51,923
as the miles ticked up,
the second, more pressing issue

696
00:40:51,923 --> 00:40:55,723
was that the scenery was
getting bigger.

697
00:40:55,723 --> 00:40:57,363
You look to your left,

698
00:40:57,363 --> 00:41:01,043
you've just got
a tree-and-foliage-covered mountain

699
00:41:01,043 --> 00:41:03,643
with a vast amount
of weather coming off it.

700
00:41:03,643 --> 00:41:06,563
Look at the moisture coming off
these hills.

701
00:41:06,563 --> 00:41:09,803
Can you say "look at the moisture
coming off these hills" again

702
00:41:09,803 --> 00:41:11,283
but a little bit slower?

703
00:41:15,923 --> 00:41:18,723
This is ominous.
We're climbing up a hill.

704
00:41:21,043 --> 00:41:24,643
Yeah, it's starting to get
tarmac-y now.

705
00:41:34,963 --> 00:41:39,163
I've got a funny feeling
this is more D-Max country.

706
00:41:39,163 --> 00:41:42,043
Oh, this is what the D-Max loves.

707
00:41:42,043 --> 00:41:45,163
Ooh-oh.

708
00:41:52,403 --> 00:41:55,643
Oh, this looks like it's too much
for me.

709
00:41:55,643 --> 00:41:57,803
Come on, then, little fella.

710
00:41:59,283 --> 00:42:01,003
CAR CLATTERS

711
00:42:01,003 --> 00:42:02,483
It's sounding good, this.

712
00:42:02,483 --> 00:42:03,923
Oh, my Lord.

713
00:42:03,923 --> 00:42:05,323
Oh, God.

714
00:42:06,803 --> 00:42:10,523
The D-Max absolutely loves
this terrain.

715
00:42:10,523 --> 00:42:12,923
Power, power, power.

716
00:42:12,923 --> 00:42:14,683
Power, power, power!

717
00:42:16,283 --> 00:42:17,723
Come on, old girl.

718
00:42:19,123 --> 00:42:20,243
Come on, old girl.

719
00:42:20,243 --> 00:42:23,163
This is where the two-wheel drive
has been found out, Chris.

720
00:42:23,163 --> 00:42:26,163
She's struggling now.
This is like live Jenga.

721
00:42:27,883 --> 00:42:30,883
Oh, your load's looking
a little bit wobbly, there, Chris.

722
00:42:32,043 --> 00:42:34,243
Stop! You've lost a bale.

723
00:42:34,243 --> 00:42:36,443
You've lost a bale, son.

724
00:42:36,443 --> 00:42:37,843
Come back.

725
00:42:37,843 --> 00:42:39,923
I can't lose a bale.

726
00:42:39,923 --> 00:42:42,163
Keep coming.  How far back
can I come?

727
00:42:42,163 --> 00:42:44,683
Keep coming. That'll do you.

728
00:42:49,803 --> 00:42:51,083
Shall we just lob it up?

729
00:42:51,083 --> 00:42:52,843
You ready? One, two, three.

730
00:42:57,043 --> 00:42:58,563
Well, it sort of worked.

731
00:43:01,723 --> 00:43:06,963
Back on the move, though, our
oversized and badly lashed cargo

732
00:43:06,963 --> 00:43:11,163
was quickly becoming the least
of Harris's concerns.

733
00:43:12,203 --> 00:43:14,003
I've got an issue -
my air con's gone

734
00:43:14,003 --> 00:43:15,643
and also I've lost the front window,

735
00:43:15,643 --> 00:43:17,763
so I'm just sitting, literally,
in an oven now.

736
00:43:18,843 --> 00:43:20,883
Sitrep on the D-Max.

737
00:43:22,443 --> 00:43:23,923
Everything's fine.

738
00:43:24,963 --> 00:43:28,723
Aircon's blowing a bit extreme,
though. Bit chilly in here.

739
00:43:31,683 --> 00:43:38,923
3 Series with a black vinyl interior
in this heat is a hot place to be.

740
00:43:41,843 --> 00:43:44,163
I can't deal with this.

741
00:43:44,163 --> 00:43:46,643
This heat is just absurd.

742
00:43:49,683 --> 00:43:55,083
And so my slow coupe colleague set
about redesigning the ventilation

743
00:43:55,083 --> 00:43:56,243
on his Beemer.

744
00:43:57,443 --> 00:43:59,003
What are you doing?

745
00:44:03,283 --> 00:44:05,523
I've broken the door
but not the window.

746
00:44:08,883 --> 00:44:10,283
What are you doing?

747
00:44:10,283 --> 00:44:13,523
Just trying to deal with my
ventilation issues at the moment.

748
00:44:13,523 --> 00:44:16,043
I'm just going to have a minute
to contemplate it

749
00:44:16,043 --> 00:44:17,203
if you don't mind, Pad.

750
00:44:17,203 --> 00:44:20,923
So, the place to contemplate it
is on a steep gradient

751
00:44:20,923 --> 00:44:22,323
on a gravel track?

752
00:44:23,483 --> 00:44:25,323
Oh, my God. What are you doing?

753
00:44:25,323 --> 00:44:27,963
I've got to get rid of that glass.
I can't breathe.

754
00:44:27,963 --> 00:44:29,163
What?

755
00:44:30,683 --> 00:44:32,683
Great work.

756
00:44:32,683 --> 00:44:34,643
Ha-ha, ha!

757
00:44:35,763 --> 00:44:39,763
I feel like this is a job
for a man from Bolton.

758
00:44:39,763 --> 00:44:41,683
Watch yourself, son.

